{
  "response": "# Button Bar Accessibility Design Plan\n\n> **For Claude:** Use a11y-planner protocol. Review with a11y-critic after implementation.\n> **Compliance target:** WCAG 2.2 AA\n> **Users who need accessibility:** Keyboard-only users, screen reader users (NVDA), low-vision users (focus visibility, color distinction)\n> **Assistive technologies:** NVDA, keyboard-only navigation. Should also work with JAWS/VoiceOver since the pattern is native HTML.\n\n**Feature:** A reusable horizontal bar of three icon+text action buttons (Save, Cancel, Delete), each triggering a distinct action.\n**Risk Level:** Low\n**Component Type:** Button group (three independent native buttons)\n\n---\n\n## Scope & Context\n\n1. **What is being built?** A reusable, statically-positioned horizontal bar containing three independent action buttons: Save, Cancel, and Delete.\n2. **What user need does it address?** Lets users commit, abandon, or destroy the current record/form via clear, labeled controls.\n3. **Who needs accessibility?**\n   - Keyboard-only users (must reach and activate every button without a mouse).\n   - Screen reader users / NVDA (must hear the name, role, and \u2014 for Delete \u2014 the destructive nature).\n   - Low-vision users (must see which button has focus, and must distinguish the destructive Delete button without relying on color alone).\n4. **Compliance target:** WCAG 2.2 AA.\n5. **Assistive technologies to support:** NVDA + keyboard explicitly required. Native `<button>` semantics make this portable to JAWS and VoiceOver for free.\n6. **Risk level:** **Low.** Three independent native buttons with no composite-widget behavior, no dynamic insertion/removal, no overlay, no focus trapping. The only real risks are (a) icon-only or icon+text labeling, (b) focus indicator contrast, and (c) communicating \"Delete is destructive\" by more than color.\n7. **What existing code does this modify/extend?** None \u2014 new component.\n8. **Constraints:**\n   - The fixture notes icons may render icon-only at some sizes (\"Icon-only buttons (need accessible labels)\"). The plan must ensure an accessible name survives even if the visible text is hidden.\n   - The three actions are independent \u2014 this is **not** a toolbar that should use roving tabindex or arrow-key navigation. It is a simple button group; each button is a normal tab stop.\n\n### Decision: button group, NOT APG Toolbar\n\nThe APG Toolbar pattern (`https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/toolbar/`) groups controls under a single tab stop with arrow-key navigation between them. That pattern earns its keystrokes when a toolbar has *many* controls and you want to reduce the number of Tab presses to get past it (e.g., a rich-text editor).\n\nFor **three** equally-important, independent actions, Toolbar is the wrong choice: it would make arrow keys mandatory, add `tabindex=\"-1\"`/roving-tabindex machinery, and surprise users who expect three normal tab stops. The simplest correct pattern is three native `<button>` elements, each a normal tab stop, per the APG Button pattern (`https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/`). This is the calibrated choice for a TRIVIAL component \u2014 do not over-engineer.\n\n---\n\n## Semantic Structure Plan\n\n**Landmarks:** A reusable button bar does not own a landmark by itself; it lives inside whatever region the host places it in (e.g., a `<form>`'s submit area, a dialog footer, a card). Do not wrap it in `<main>`/`<nav>`. If grouping is semantically useful to the host, wrap the three buttons in a `<div role=\"group\">` with an accessible name (see below) \u2014 but `role=\"group\"` is **optional** here and adds little for three buttons. WCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships.\n\n**Heading hierarchy:** None \u2014 a button bar introduces no headings. (Do not invent an `<h_>` for it.)\n\n**Semantic elements:**\n\n| Region | Element | Why | WCAG |\n|--------|---------|-----|------|\n| The bar container | `<div role=\"group\" aria-label=\"Record actions\">` (optional) | If used, communicates that the three buttons are a related set. Skip if it adds noise. | 1.3.1 |\n| Each action | `<button type=\"button\">` | Native button gives keyboard activation (Enter + Space), focusability, and the `button` role for free. Avoids re-implementing behavior on a `<div>`. | 4.1.2, 2.1.1 |\n\n**`type` attribute matters.** If this bar ever sits inside a `<form>`, set `type=\"button\"` on Cancel and Delete so they do **not** submit the form. Save may use `type=\"submit\"` if it is the form's submit action, otherwise `type=\"button\"`. Defaulting to `type=\"submit\"` (the HTML default inside a form) on Cancel/Delete is a real bug \u2014 document it now so the implementer chooses deliberately.\n\n**HTML structure stub** (structure only \u2014 not implementation code):\n\n```\n<div role=\"group\" aria-label=\"Record actions\">        <!-- optional grouping -->\n  <button type=\"submit\" aria-label=\"Save\">             <!-- or type=\"button\" -->\n    <svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\">\u2026</svg>   <!-- decorative icon -->\n    <span>Save</span>                                    <!-- visible text label -->\n  </button>\n  <button type=\"button\" aria-label=\"Cancel\">\n    <svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\">\u2026</svg>\n    <span>Cancel</span>\n  </button>\n  <button type=\"button\" aria-label=\"Delete\">\n    <svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\">\u2026</svg>\n    <span>Delete</span>\n  </button>\n</div>\n```\n\nNotes on the stub:\n- When the visible `<span>` text **is** present, the button's accessible name comes from the text \u2014 the `aria-label` is redundant and should be **omitted** to avoid the risk of the two disagreeing. List `aria-label` here only for the icon-only rendering (next section).\n- The icon is decorative because the adjacent text already names the button. `aria-hidden=\"true\"` on the `<svg>` keeps NVDA from announcing icon internals; `focusable=\"false\"` stops legacy IE/Edge from making the SVG a tab stop. WCAG 1.1.1 Non-text Content.\n\n---\n\n## Interaction Pattern Design\n\nEvery button maps to the **APG Button pattern**: `https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/`.\n\nBecause these are native `<button>` elements, the browser supplies the entire keyboard and role model \u2014 we are not reconstructing it on a generic element. That is the whole reason to use `<button>`.\n\n### Keyboard interaction model (per button)\n\n- **Tab** \u2192 moves focus to this button (and Shift+Tab moves backward). Each button is its own tab stop. WCAG 2.1.1 Keyboard.\n- **Enter** \u2192 activates the button (fires its click handler). Native default. WCAG 2.1.1.\n- **Space** \u2192 activates the button on key-up. Native default. WCAG 2.1.1.\n- **No arrow-key navigation** \u2014 intentional. These are independent buttons, not a composite toolbar.\n\n### ARIA implementation (per button)\n\n- Role: `button` \u2014 provided natively by `<button>`; do **not** add `role=\"button\"`.\n- No `aria-pressed` \u2014 these are action buttons, not toggle buttons (Save/Cancel/Delete are one-shot actions with no on/off state).\n- No `aria-expanded` \u2014 none of them disclose a region.\n- Accessible name: from visible `<span>` text, or `aria-label` when icon-only (see Content Accessibility Plan).\n\n### Screen reader experience (NVDA)\n\n- On focus, NVDA announces: **\"Save, button\"** / **\"Cancel, button\"** / **\"Delete, button\"** (name + role). No state to announce because these are stateless action buttons.\n- On activation, the *consequence* (record saved, dialog closed, item deleted) is the host application's responsibility to announce \u2014 typically via a live region or a focus move to a confirmation. That announcement belongs to the host flow, not this reusable bar; flag it as a host integration note rather than building a live region into the bar itself. (See Failure Modes.)\n\n### Interactive Elements Table\n\n| Widget | APG Pattern | Keyboard | ARIA | WCAG |\n|--------|-------------|----------|------|------|\n| Save button | [Button](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/) | Tab focus; Enter/Space activate | native `button` role; name from text or `aria-label`; `type=\"submit\"` or `\"button\"` | 2.1.1, 4.1.2, 1.1.1 |\n| Cancel button | [Button](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/) | Tab focus; Enter/Space activate | native `button` role; name from text or `aria-label`; `type=\"button\"` | 2.1.1, 4.1.2, 1.1.1 |\n| Delete button | [Button](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/) | Tab focus; Enter/Space activate | native `button` role; name from text or `aria-label`; `type=\"button\"` | 2.1.1, 4.1.2, 1.1.1 |\n\n---\n\n## Focus Management Plan\n\n1. **Tab order:** Save \u2192 Cancel \u2192 Delete, matching the visual left-to-right order. This falls out of DOM order automatically when the buttons appear in this order in the markup \u2014 do **not** use `tabindex` values greater than 0 to reorder. WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order; WCAG 1.3.2 Meaningful Sequence.\n2. **Visual order = DOM order:** Author the buttons in DOM in the same Save/Cancel/Delete order they render. Do not use CSS (`flex-direction: row-reverse`, `order:`) to visually reorder them away from DOM order, which would desync the tab sequence from the reading order. WCAG 2.4.3.\n3. **No focus trap.** This is not a modal; Tab must be able to leave the bar in both directions. (A focus trap here would be a WCAG 2.1.2 No Keyboard Trap failure.)\n4. **No focus restoration logic inside the bar.** The bar opens no overlay, so it has nothing to restore. If activating a button (e.g., Cancel closing a dialog) changes context, restoring focus is the **host** flow's job, not the bar's. Note it as an integration concern.\n5. **Focus indicator must be visible** on every button at every zoom level, meeting non-text contrast \u2014 see Visual Accessibility Plan. WCAG 2.4.7 Focus Visible.\n6. **No roving tabindex** \u2014 correct for a non-composite button group. All three buttons keep their default `tabindex` (none).\n7. **No skip link** \u2014 three adjacent buttons are not a \"block\" worth bypassing per WCAG 2.4.1; a skip link would be over-engineering for this component.\n\n---\n\n## State Communication Design\n\nThese are **stateless action buttons** \u2014 they have no checked/expanded/selected/pressed states. The states that *do* exist are interaction (hover/active/focus) and the optional disabled state. Each must be conveyed by more than color.\n\n### State Communication Table\n\n| State | Visual | Programmatic | ARIA | WCAG |\n|-------|--------|-------------|------|------|\n| Default / enabled | Base button styling; for Delete, a destructive treatment (icon + label, plus an outline/fill that reads as \"danger\") | Native enabled `<button>` | none needed | 1.4.1, 1.4.11 |\n| Hover | Background/elevation change | n/a (visual affordance only) | none | 1.4.11 |\n| Active (pressed-in) | Pressed/darkened visual | n/a | none | 1.4.11 |\n| Focused | **Visible focus ring** meeting 3:1 contrast (see Visual plan) | Native `:focus` | none | 2.4.7, 1.4.11 |\n| Disabled (if used) | Dimmed appearance **plus** non-color cue (e.g., reduced opacity + removal of hover affordance) | Prefer the native `disabled` attribute (removes it from tab order and from the accessibility action set). If the design requires the disabled button to stay focusable so users can discover *why* it is disabled, use `aria-disabled=\"true\"` instead and suppress the action in the handler. | `disabled` **or** `aria-disabled=\"true\"` | 1.4.1, 4.1.2 |\n\nNotes:\n- **No `aria-pressed`/`aria-expanded`/`aria-checked`/`aria-selected`** \u2014 adding any would mislead NVDA into announcing a state these buttons do not have. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- **Disabled trade-off, decide deliberately:** native `disabled` is simpler and is the right default. The fixture does not ask for a disabled state, so treat disabled as **optional**; if implemented, pick one mechanism and document why. A native-`disabled` button is silent to discovery (NVDA may skip it); `aria-disabled` keeps it discoverable but you must block the action in JS.\n- **No live region inside this reusable bar.** Action *results* (saved/deleted) should be announced by the host. Building `role=\"status\"` into the bar would fire announcements the bar has no reliable content for. Flag as host integration. WCAG 4.1.3 Status Messages (host responsibility).\n\n---\n\n## Visual Accessibility Plan\n\n1. **Color contrast (WCAG 1.4.3 Contrast Minimum):**\n   - Button label text vs. its button background: **4.5:1** for normal text, **3:1** if the label is large text (\u226518.66px, or \u226514px bold). Verify for **all three** buttons in **all** visual states (default, hover, active, disabled) and in both light and dark themes.\n   - Button boundary/fill vs. the surrounding page (so a sighted user can tell where the button is): **3:1** non-text contrast. WCAG 1.4.11 Non-text Contrast.\n   - The Delete \"danger\" color must itself meet 4.5:1 for its text and 3:1 for its boundary \u2014 a danger red that fails contrast is a common bug.\n\n2. **Focus indicator (WCAG 2.4.7 Focus Visible + WCAG 1.4.11 Non-text Contrast, 3:1):**\n   - Use a **two-color (double-ring) focus indicator**: an `outline` plus a `box-shadow` in contrasting colors (e.g., a dark outline and a light offset ring, or vice versa). A single-color outline disappears when it matches either the button or the page background; two colors guarantee at least one ring is visible against any background. The fixture explicitly requires **3:1 focus indicator contrast** \u2014 the visible ring must hit 3:1 against the adjacent color it sits on.\n   - Use **`:focus-visible`**, not `:focus`, so the ring shows for keyboard focus but not on mouse click. WCAG 2.4.7.\n   - Do **not** remove the outline (`outline: none`) without replacing it with an equally visible indicator \u2014 silent removal is the single most common focus-visibility failure.\n   - Buttons are `display: inline-block`/`flex` (block-level boxes), so the focus ring will be a clean rectangle; no inline-fragmentation concern.\n   - Watch CSS specificity: a CSS framework or browser default may override author focus styles \u2014 plan a sufficiently specific selector (or `!important` if a framework fights you).\n\n3. **Color is never the sole indicator (WCAG 1.4.1 Use of Color):**\n   - **Delete = destructive** must be communicated by **more than red**: keep the visible **text label \"Delete\"** and a recognizable **icon** (e.g., a trash can) in addition to the danger color. Color + text + icon. A colorblind user, or a user in forced-colors/high-contrast mode where the danger color is overridden, still reads \"Delete\" and sees the trash icon.\n   - Focus is communicated by a **ring shape + position**, not just a color shift.\n   - List of color-coded states and their non-color cue: **Delete/danger** \u2192 text + icon + shape; **focused** \u2192 ring shape; **disabled** (if used) \u2192 dimming + removed hover affordance + `disabled`/`aria-disabled`.\n\n4. **Touch target size (WCAG 2.5.8 Target Size (Minimum), AA):** Each button \u2265 **24\u00d724** CSS px (the AA minimum). Recommend **44\u00d744** as the stronger target (the 2.5.5 AAA size and a better mobile experience). Ensure adjacent buttons have enough spacing/size that the 24px targets do not overlap.\n\n5. **Responsive text / zoom (WCAG 1.4.4 Resize Text, 1.4.10 Reflow):**\n   - Size button padding and font in **relative units** (`rem`/`em`), not fixed `px`, so labels scale to 200% and the bar reflows to 400% zoom (320px-equivalent width) without clipping or horizontal scroll.\n   - At narrow widths the bar may wrap to multiple rows \u2014 that is fine; do not hide any button at small breakpoints (hiding a function at narrow viewports is a 1.4.10 failure). If the icon+text becomes icon-only at small sizes, the `aria-label` must already be in place (see Content plan).\n\n6. **Reduced motion (WCAG 2.3.3 Animation from Interactions):** If hover/active uses transitions, wrap motion in `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)` to disable/curtail it. Color/elevation state changes can remain; large movement should not.\n\n7. **Dark mode / forced colors (WCAG 1.4.11):** Verify all contrasts in `prefers-color-scheme: dark`. Test Windows High Contrast / `forced-colors: active`: native `<button>` adapts automatically, but confirm the focus ring and the Delete affordance still read (since custom danger colors are overridden in forced-colors \u2014 which is exactly why \"Delete\" text + icon must carry the meaning).\n\n---\n\n## Content Accessibility Plan\n\n1. **Accessible name strategy (WCAG 1.1.1, 4.1.2, 2.4.6 Headings and Labels):**\n   - **When visible text is shown** (`<span>Save</span>` etc.): the visible text **is** the accessible name. Do not also add `aria-label` \u2014 duplicate/divergent names are a defect and `aria-label` would override the visible text, breaking voice-control users who say \"click Save.\" Visible-label-and-name match supports WCAG 2.5.3 Label in Name.\n   - **When the button renders icon-only** (the fixture's constraint): the button has no visible text node, so it needs an `aria-label`:\n     - Save \u2192 `aria-label=\"Save\"`\n     - Cancel \u2192 `aria-label=\"Cancel\"`\n     - Delete \u2192 `aria-label=\"Delete\"` (consider `aria-label=\"Delete record\"` only if \"Delete\" alone is ambiguous in context \u2014 keep it matching any tooltip text).\n   - **Never use `title` as the accessible name mechanism.** `title` produces a hover tooltip that is unreliable across screen readers and invisible to keyboard/touch users. Use `aria-label` (icon-only) or visible text. This is a hard rule.\n   - **The icon itself carries no accessible name:** `aria-hidden=\"true\"` on the `<svg>` (and empty `alt=\"\"` if an `<img>` is ever used) so the icon is not announced separately. With `aria-hidden` on the icon, an `<img>` icon's `alt` must be **empty** \u2014 otherwise NVDA reads a redundant icon description alongside the real label.\n\n2. **Link/button text quality (WCAG 2.4.4 / 2.4.6):** \"Save\", \"Cancel\", \"Delete\" are already descriptive and unambiguous \u2014 no \"click here.\" Good as-is.\n\n3. **No form-field labels** \u2014 there are no inputs in this component.\n\n4. **Language:** Inherits `<html lang>` from the host page (WCAG 3.1.1). No foreign-language strings in this component.\n\n5. **Reading order (WCAG 1.3.2):** DOM order Save\u2192Cancel\u2192Delete matches visual order; do not diverge.\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n### 1. Automated (axe-core, accessibility-testing skill)\nRun axe-core on the rendered bar in **each visual state** (default, hover, active, focus, and disabled if implemented) and in **both** light and dark themes.\n- Validates: button has an accessible name, color contrast of label text, valid ARIA usage, no `aria-hidden` on a focusable element.\n- axe will **not** catch: whether the accessible name actually *matches the visible label*, focus-ring visibility, the Delete \"more than color\" requirement, or that `type` is correct inside a form. Those are manual/DOM checks below.\n\n### 2. Manual keyboard testing (a11y-test skill, real key events)\n- **Tab** reaches Save, then Cancel, then Delete, in that order; **Shift+Tab** reverses. (WCAG 2.4.3, 2.1.1)\n- Focus is **never trapped** \u2014 Tab continues past Delete to the next page control, and Shift+Tab moves before Save. (WCAG 2.1.2)\n- **Enter** activates the focused button; **Space** activates the focused button. Verify each of the three handlers actually fires. (WCAG 2.1.1)\n- The **focus ring is clearly visible** on each button, including at **200% and 400% zoom**, and in dark mode. (WCAG 2.4.7)\n- If inside a `<form>`: confirm **Cancel and Delete do not submit** the form, and Save behaves as intended. (functional correctness of `type`)\n\n### 3. Screen reader testing (NVDA, real AT)\n- Tabbing to each button announces **name + role**, e.g., \"Save, button.\" (WCAG 4.1.2)\n- In **icon-only** mode, the `aria-label` is what NVDA reads \u2014 confirm it announces \"Save/Cancel/Delete, button\" and **not** an SVG path, file name, or nothing. (WCAG 1.1.1, 4.1.2)\n- The icon is **not** announced separately (confirms `aria-hidden=\"true\"` is working).\n- No phantom state is announced (no \"pressed\", \"expanded\", \"selected\").\n\n### 4. Visual regression / forced-colors\n- Focus indicator visible in a screenshot of each focused button.\n- 200% and 400% zoom: bar reflows (may wrap) with **no clipped labels and no horizontal scroll**, all three buttons still present. (WCAG 1.4.4, 1.4.10)\n- **Forced-colors / Windows High Contrast:** focus ring still visible; \"Delete\" text + icon still convey destructiveness once the custom danger color is overridden. (WCAG 1.4.1, 1.4.11)\n\n### 5. DOM verification (required \u2014 not optional)\nInspect the rendered DOM (not just the source) to confirm:\n- Each control is a real `<button>`, **not** a `<div>`/`<span>` with a click handler.\n- Accessible name resolves correctly: in text mode it comes from the visible `<span>`; in icon-only mode `aria-label` is present and correct.\n- `aria-hidden=\"true\"` lands on the **icon**, never on the button, and no focusable element is inside an `aria-hidden` subtree.\n- No `title`-as-name; no stray `role=\"button\"`; no `tabindex > 0`.\n- Correct `type` on each button for the form context.\n\n### Acceptance criteria (what \"accessible\" means here)\n- \u2705 Three native `<button>` elements, reachable and activatable by **Tab + Enter + Space**, in left-to-right order, with no keyboard trap.\n- \u2705 Every button exposes a correct accessible name in **both** text and icon-only renderings; the name matches the visible label when text is shown.\n- \u2705 Focus indicator meets **3:1** non-text contrast and is visible at 100/200/400% zoom and in dark/forced-colors.\n- \u2705 Delete's destructive nature is conveyed by **text + icon + shape**, not color alone.\n- \u2705 Label text meets 4.5:1 (or 3:1 if large) in all states/themes.\n- \u2705 axe-core passes on all state variants; DOM verification confirms attribute placement.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Tasks\n\n### Task 1: Button Bar component (Save / Cancel / Delete)\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint**\n\n**Files:** `components/ButtonBar.{tsx|vue|twig}`, `components/ButtonBar.test.{ts|js}`, `components/ButtonBar.css`\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n```\n<div role=\"group\" aria-label=\"Record actions\">          <!-- grouping optional -->\n  <button type=\"submit\">  <svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\"/> <span>Save</span>   </button>\n  <button type=\"button\">  <svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\"/> <span>Cancel</span> </button>\n  <button type=\"button\">  <svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\"/> <span>Delete</span> </button>\n</div>\n<!-- Icon-only rendering: drop the <span>, add aria-label=\"Save\"/\"Cancel\"/\"Delete\" to the <button> -->\n```\n\n**ARIA / attributes required:**\n- `<button>` native `role=\"button\"` \u2014 do not add manually. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-label` on each button **only in icon-only mode**; omitted when visible text is present. WCAG 1.1.1, 4.1.2, 2.5.3.\n- `aria-hidden=\"true\"` + `focusable=\"false\"` on each icon. WCAG 1.1.1.\n- Correct `type` per form context (`submit` for Save if it submits; `button` for Cancel/Delete). Functional, prevents accidental submit.\n- Optional `role=\"group\"` + `aria-label` on the container. WCAG 1.3.1.\n- Optional disabled state: native `disabled` (default) **or** `aria-disabled=\"true\"` + JS guard (only if discoverability is required). WCAG 4.1.2.\n\n**Keyboard interactions to implement:** Rely on native button behavior \u2014 Tab focus, Enter activate, Space activate. No custom key handlers, no arrow keys, no `tabindex`. WCAG 2.1.1.\n\n**Focus management:** None beyond native focusability + a visible `:focus-visible` ring (two-color, 3:1). No trap, no restoration (host's job). WCAG 2.4.7.\n\n**State communication:** Hover/active/focus via CSS; Delete danger via text+icon+color; no ARIA state attributes. WCAG 1.4.1, 1.4.11.\n\n**Tests:**\n- Tab order Save\u2192Cancel\u2192Delete; Shift+Tab reverses; not trapped.\n- Enter and Space each fire each button's handler.\n- Accessible name correct in text mode (from `<span>`) and icon-only mode (from `aria-label`); names match visible labels.\n- NVDA announces \"name, button\"; icon not announced; no phantom state.\n- Focus ring visible and \u22653:1 at 100/200/400% zoom, light/dark/forced-colors.\n- Label contrast 4.5:1 (or 3:1 large) in all states.\n- DOM check: real `<button>`s, `aria-hidden` on icons only, correct `type`, no `title`-as-name, no `tabindex>0`.\n\n**WCAG criteria satisfied:** 1.1.1, 1.3.1, 1.3.2, 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 1.4.4, 1.4.10, 1.4.11, 2.1.1, 2.1.2, 2.4.3, 2.4.6, 2.4.7, 2.5.3, 2.5.8, 2.3.3, 4.1.2.\n\n**a11y-critic checkpoint \ud83d\udd0d:** Verify (1) APG Button pattern used \u2014 native `<button>`, not `<div>`; (2) accessible name resolves in both text and icon-only renderings and matches the visible label (no `title` misuse); (3) icons are `aria-hidden`; (4) focus indicator is two-color and meets 3:1; (5) Delete destructiveness is conveyed by more than color; (6) no inappropriate ARIA state attributes; (7) correct `type` for form context; (8) no keyboard trap and natural left-to-right tab order.\n\n---\n\n## a11y-Critic Review Checkpoints\n\n| Checkpoint | After Task | Focus |\n|-----------|-----------|-------|\n| \ud83d\udd0d 1 | Task 1 | Native button semantics; accessible name in text + icon-only modes (matches visible label, no `title`); icons `aria-hidden`; focus indicator two-color \u22653:1; Delete = more than color; no phantom ARIA state; correct `type`; natural tab order, no trap; DOM-verified attribute placement |\n\n---\n\n### Contract Appendix (for spec-kitty-bridge WP translation)\n\n### Architecture Overview\nThree independent native `<button>` elements rendered left-to-right (optionally wrapped in `role=\"group\"`). All keyboard and role behavior is delegated to native HTML \u2014 no composite-widget/roving-tabindex machinery (this is a button group, not an APG Toolbar). Accessible names come from visible text, or `aria-label` in icon-only mode; icons are `aria-hidden`. State communication is purely interaction state (hover/active/focus) plus an optional disabled state; there are no toggle/selection states and therefore no `aria-pressed`/`aria-expanded`. Focus visibility is delivered by a two-color `:focus-visible` ring meeting 3:1; Delete's destructive nature is conveyed by text + icon + shape, not color alone. Action *results* and any post-action focus moves are explicitly the host application's responsibility, not this reusable bar's.\n\n### Implementation Tasks\n\n#### Task 1: Button Bar component (Save / Cancel / Delete)\nEstimated Effort: low\nDepends on: none\n\n#### Test Strategy for Task 1\nAutomated axe-core on every state/theme variant; manual real-key keyboard testing (Tab/Shift+Tab order, no trap, Enter + Space activation); NVDA name+role announcement in both text and icon-only renderings with icons silent; visual-regression focus-ring + 200%/400% zoom reflow + forced-colors checks; and a mandatory DOM-inspection pass confirming native `<button>`, `aria-hidden` on icons only, correct `type`, no `title`-as-name, and no `tabindex>0`.\n\n#### Acceptance Criteria for Task 1\n- Three native `<button>`s reachable/activatable by Tab + Enter + Space, left-to-right, no keyboard trap (WCAG 2.1.1, 2.1.2, 2.4.3).\n- Correct accessible name in text and icon-only modes, matching visible label (WCAG 1.1.1, 4.1.2, 2.5.3); `aria-label` used for icon-only, never `title`.\n- Icons `aria-hidden=\"true\"` + `focusable=\"false\"`; no focusable element inside an `aria-hidden` subtree (WCAG 1.1.1).\n- Focus indicator two-color, \u22653:1 non-text contrast, visible at 100/200/400% zoom and in dark/forced-colors (WCAG 2.4.7, 1.4.11).\n- Delete destructiveness conveyed by text + icon + shape, not color alone (WCAG 1.4.1).\n- Label text \u22654.5:1 (or 3:1 if large) across all states/themes (WCAG 1.4.3); targets \u226524\u00d724 CSS px (WCAG 2.5.8).\n- No `aria-pressed`/`aria-expanded`/`aria-checked`/`aria-selected`; correct `type` per form context (WCAG 4.1.2).\n\n### Failure Modes\n- **`<div>`/`<span>` \"button\"** with a click handler \u2192 loses Enter/Space activation, focusability, and `button` role. Use native `<button>`. (WCAG 2.1.1, 4.1.2)\n- **Icon-only with no `aria-label`** \u2192 NVDA announces nothing, an SVG path, or a file name. Add `aria-label`. (WCAG 1.1.1)\n- **`aria-label` left on a button that also shows visible text** \u2192 name/label divergence; overrides the visible word and breaks \"click Save\" voice control. Omit `aria-label` when text is shown. (WCAG 2.5.3)\n- **`title` used as the accessible name** \u2192 tooltip only; unreliable across SR, invisible to keyboard/touch. Never the name mechanism.\n- **`outline: none` with no replacement, or a single-color ring** \u2192 focus invisible against matching backgrounds. Use a two-color `:focus-visible` ring at 3:1. (WCAG 2.4.7)\n- **Delete signaled by red alone** \u2192 invisible to colorblind users and lost in forced-colors. Keep text + icon. (WCAG 1.4.1)\n- **Wrong `type` inside a form** \u2192 Cancel/Delete accidentally submit. Set `type=\"button\"` on non-submit actions.\n- **Phantom ARIA state** (`aria-pressed`/`aria-expanded` on a stateless action button) \u2192 NVDA announces a state that does not exist. Omit. (WCAG 4.1.2)\n- **`tabindex` > 0 to \"order\" buttons** \u2192 desyncs tab order from reading order. Rely on DOM order. (WCAG 2.4.3)\n- **Assuming the bar must announce the action result** \u2192 over-build of a live region with no reliable content; the result/announcement and any focus move belong to the host flow. Document as integration note, don't bake into the reusable bar. (WCAG 4.1.3)\n",
